20. composita (s): prearrangement is the point3 hence the order. But see P. 21. *

21, 22. latentis...angulo: for the grouping see on P. 6. For the normal group gratus puellae risus see Odes 1. 7. 29.

23. lacertis: for its position see P. 47.

X. 1. facunde (p): see on P. 36; but for the groupfizcunde nepos Atlantis see on P. 35.

2. feros cultus hominum: for grouping see on P. 35.

3, 4. catus sc. ὤν. Compare puer at Odes 1. 9. 16.

decorae (p): grace, in place of uncouthness‚ is the point.

decorae 1 more palaestrae: for the grouping see on P. 2011.

5. magni...deorum: the genitives are preposited because Mercury is no mere lackey of nonentities, but envoy of great Jove and the gods.

6. curvae (p): the epithet refers to the bellied shape of the real or imita- tion tortoise—shell which formed a sounding-board‚ contrasted with the square box of the cithara. In any case curvus is always prepositive in Horace. See too odes 3. 28. 11.

lyrae (ffiz the order, perhaps, suggests the antithesis of orator (sacumle l. 1), and envoy (nuntium l. 6), to musician (lyrae); but it is possible to com— pare the order of Andromedae pater at Odes 3. 29. 17. See P. 41 adfin.

7. iocoso (ps) i.e. in jest, as isper iocum; see P. 31, and also P. 21.

9. te, boves olim: for case relations grouped early i.e. ‘the old story (olim) os you and the oxen,' see on Otles 1. 2. 17. There is no need to place a comma after te or after amotas.
